content: # QUARTERLY NEWSLETTER # Promoting Data Protection and Cyber Security # JAN - MAR 2025 # CAPACITY BUILDING # SKILL DEVELOPMENT THROUGH DSCI CERTIFICATIONS | Professionals Trained: 21 | Professionals Trained: 29 | Professionals Trained: 62 | Professionals Trained: 40 | Professionals Trained: 35 | | ------------------------- | ------------------------- | ------------------------- | ------------------------- | ------------------------- | | Batches Conducted: 5 | | | | | | Batch: 12ᵗʰ | | | | | Wrapped up the pilot batch of the DSCI Certiﬁed Quantum Technology & Security Professional (DCQTSP) in partnership with QNu Labs in Bangalore. With a special focus on quantum technologies, the 3-day program brought together experts from academia, ISRO, finance, energy, aerospace, and more, fostering rich cross-sector insights. Participants also engaged hands-on with real quantum hardware like QRNGs and QKD systems. The 2nd batch of the 3-day executive DSCI Certiﬁed Strategist Program, held in Mumbai, equipped executive leaders with in-depth knowledge of cybersecurity and privacy governance, where participants came from organizations like Worldline Global Services Pvt. Ltd., Saarth Infosec Private Limited, Angel One Limited, CDS, Kyndryl, AIS Business Solutions Pvt. Ltd., and Fin Soft Solutions. Cyber Sainik, in collaboration with Kyndryl, successfully concluded the final phase of its first edition in Mangaluru, Karnataka, impacting 600+ beneficiaries. The sessions covered essential cyber safety topics, including cyberspace basics, internet functionality, social media risks, cyberbullying, grooming, and stalking. The Cyber for HER hackathon curated for young women aged 18-23 was concluded with support from the British High Commission, New Delhi and sponsored by Rubrik. Around 1,300+ registrations and 550+ submissions on themes- Cyber Awareness, Digital Hygiene, and Privacy Protection were received during phase one. In phase two, 200 shortlisted candidates then competed against each other for the in-person hackathon. The winning team, the first and second runners-up received cash prizes worth INR 2,00,000/-, INR 1,50,000/-, and INR 70,000/- respectively. | Winner | 1st Runner-up | 2nd Runner-up | | ------------------ | ------------- | -------------- | | Team Fallen\_Order | Team Nova | Team ArthSutra | DSCI’s joint women skilling initiative with Microsoft, CyberShikshaa had 115 students complete the program with 50% successful placements. This year, the spectrum of recruiters increased with Nvidia Corporation India, Finance Dept. Govt. of Tripura, Co-operative Bank -Thrissur, Luminar Technolab, Calicut, Govt. of Kerala Panchayat E-Services, Alappuzha, Trimax, Cochin and SIBIN Group coming onboard. The third batch of the program was recently launched in Mohali, Punjab, in collaboration with Kyndryl Foundation. The program engaged 35 young learners, marking a return for the initiatives in the state. The joint initiative with Kyndryl India, CyberVaahini is currently training batches in Pune and Kolkata for the cyber skilling of 100 women from tier-II and tier-III cities as proposed under the program. On the occasion of International Women’s Day, an expert session for CyberVaahini students was organized on ‘How Organizations Operate in Cyber Ecosystem with Today's AI Threats and Cloud Security Aspects.’ The session was taken by Ms. Sunanda Lalchandani, Director, DEFEND Platform India Lead & Global ISO 27001 Program Lead (ISMS) BNY India. Students from Pune and Kolkata batch were also a part of the engaging discussion. A 10-day IIT Jammu Comprehensive Cyber Security Competency Development Programme (CDP) was specially designed for IES/ITS officers at DSCI, Noida campus. This specialized program empowered officers with industry insights and cutting-edge capabilities to safeguard India's critical communications through: strategic cybersecurity planning, digital forensics expertise, and advanced threat detection. The program concluded with a felicitation ceremony for over 30 participants. # GLOBAL TRADE AND DEVELOPMENT DSCI joined the Cybersec Asia opening ceremony, leading a delegation of six Indian cybersecurity companies showcasing their innovative solutions. A special session, “India-Thailand Cybersecurity Connect: Spotlight on Innovation,” saw participation from Thailand’s NCSA, industry associations, tech bodies, and government authorities, highlighting a strong commitment to cross-border cybersecurity cooperation.

content: # THOUGHT LEADERSHIP # LATEST THREAT ADVISORIES | READ PAPER | READ ADVISORY | READ ADVISORY | READ ADVISORY | | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- | -------------------------- | | iPhone Forensics – Methods, Tools and Best Practices | Threat Advisory (Jan 2025) | Threat Advisory (Feb 2025) | Threat Advisory (Mar 2025) | | iPhones are widely used across all age groups making them a critical source of digital evidence in criminal investigations. This paper provides essential insights into handling and analysing iPhones for forensic purposes. | Exploiting Fortinet Firewalls: A Deep Dive into Recent Zero-day Vulnerability | Google Account Takeover Scams using AI calls | Emerging Cyber Threats | | In this threat advisory, read in detail about a campaign that involved suspicious activity on Fortinet FortiGate Firewalls devices CVE-2024-50603 leading to a zero-day vulnerability. | | | | | This threat advisory exposes AI-driven phishing scams and banking malware threats, offering key insights and security recommendations. | | | | | This threat advisory explores and highlights the emerging cyber threats, including a stealthy credential-stealing malware and a brute force attack framework. | | | | # AWARENESS AND OUTREACH The Cyber for Bharat initiative has been started to extend cybersecurity dialogues and engagement beyond metro cities initiative. The pilot session engaged with the talent community of Bhimavaram in association with DSCI member, Netenrich Technologies. The session comprised a facility walkthrough, capability discussions, and strategic insights to enhance the local potential. Following this, the team engaged with the talent pool of Mysuru in association with the Cyberverse Foundation. Cities covered till now: Bhimavaram and Mysuru. # CYBER SECURITY GRAND CHALLENGE 2.0 (CSGC2.0) Cyber Security Grand Challenge (CSGC) is a joint initiative by MeitY and DSCI to boost innovation and entrepreneurship in cybersecurity. The first edition ran from January 2020 to November 2021, with a prize pool of ₹3.2 Crores and support from top government leaders. Now, CSGC 2.0 is set to launch with even more excitement, a larger prize pool of ₹6.85 Crores and new features. | Recognize top startups | Support 36 early-stage startups (3x more than last time) | Include a new “Go-To-Market” stage, in addition to Idea, MVP, and Final stages | Offer technical and business mentorship | | ---------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------- | CSGC 2.0 aims to make India a global cybersecurity leader by empowering startups & inspiring future cyber talent. # DATA PRIVACY DAY 2025 Data Privacy Day (DPD), observed annually on January 28, is a global initiative dedicated to raising awareness about data protection and privacy. This year’s central theme, 'Privacy in the Age of AI', addressed the evolving challenges and opportunities presented by AI. In this new era, prioritizing data privacy and building a foundation of trust through proactive privacy practices is vital for both individuals and businesses. This campaign was made possible with the support of our partners: Cred, IIFL, Kempegowda International Airport Bengaluru, Punjab National Bank, Protec .ai, PrivaSapien, Seqrite, and ZS Associates. # Key Themes Delivered for Organizations and Citizens: - Understanding and managing privacy settings & privacy policies - Addressing AI-enhanced scams and the growing threat of deepfakes - Practicing healthy privacy habits and safe social media sharing - Controlling app access and managing permissions effectively - Safeguarding consumer data on AI-assisted personal devices - Recognizing one's digital footprint in the age of AI - Protecting children’s privacy in AI-driven environments - Privacy-conscious implementation of AI across key business functions such as HR, marketing & advertising, product design, and sales - General recommendations for the mindful use of AI by organizations Visit Campaign: www.dsci.in/data-privacy-day-2025/ # 43 MILLION CAMPAIGN OUTREACH # DSCI DATA PROTECTION SUMMIT (DDPS) 2025 Concluded the 1st edition of DDPS 2025 to discuss how organizations can navigate the DPDP Act and created a dialogue in transforming compliance into trust.

content: | 380 Attendees | 6 Special Sessions | 218 Delegates | 3 Roundtables | 90+ Speakers | 3 Workshops | 12 Sponsors | 1 Masterclass | | ------------- | ------------------ | ------------- | ------------- | ------------ | ----------- | ----------- | ------------- | # Key Themes Delivered - Notice & consent workshop - Privacy by design - Privacy Enhancing Technologies (PET) solutions - Responsible AI & privacy strategies - Privacy program building frameworks - SDF mandates: DPIA & audits - DPDP Act implementation guidance # SECURITY CHIPS: DSCI PODCAST CHANNEL # EPISODE #14 THE UNTOLD STORY OF INDIA’S DATA PROTECTION JOURNEY Guest: Rakesh Maheshwari Ex Sr. Director and GC (Cyber Laws and Data Governance), MeitY Host: Shivangi Malhotra, Senior Associate, Privacy & Policy, DSCI LISTEN TO DSCI PODCAST # CENTRES OF EXCELLENCE # NATIONAL CENTRE OF EXCELLENCE (NCOE) Released five whitepapers, delving into key cybersecurity challenges and emerging solutions. These publications offer valuable insights into critical areas, namely: | READ WHITEPAPER | READ WHITEPAPER | READ WHITEPAPER | READ WHITEPAPER | READ WHITEPAPER | | ---------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------ | | Exploratory Note on Federated Learning in Healthcare | Privacy and Piracy Issues in Hardware Security | Healthcare Security in the Internet of Medical Things (IoMT) Environment | Integrating Post-Quantum Cryptography in Telecom | Healthcare Security & Smart Authentication | # CENTER FOR CYBERCRIME INVESTIGATION TRAINING & RESEARCH (CCITR) 3111 officers trained including judicial officers, officers from the National Investigation Agency (NIA) and Internal Security Division (ISD), Police Personnel, Police Personnel from CID, Bengaluru city, Vijayapura district, and the Corps of Military Police (CMP). 1669 police personnel trained across 13 virtual training sessions on topics including Password Cracking using Free and Open-source Tools, Darkweb Investigation Techniques, Network Scanning using Nmap, CDR Analysis Techniques, IPDR Analysis Techniques, Introduction to MAC Forensics, Cryptocurrency Investigation using Tracing Tools, and more. Conducted 20 training programs for judicial officers, officers from NIA and ISD, and police personnel from district and Bengaluru city CEN police stations on Cyber Law and Crimes, Darkweb and Social Media Monitoring, Drone Forensics, Cybercrime Investigation Techniques level 1&2, Build your PC, AI for Police, Wearable Device Forensics, and Digital Forensics Analysis of Embedded Devices and Systems. Conducted CIDCODE tech hackathon in partnership with PES University and CIDECODE cyber law ideathon with KLE Law College, where winners were awarded INR 3,00,000/- and INR 2,00,000/- respectively. Concluded the second edition of CIDECODE Summit, jointly hosted with CID Karnataka and Infosys Foundation, facilitating knowledge exchange among Law Enforcement Professionals (LEAs) while fostering professional networks. The honorable G. Parameshwara, Home Minister of Karnataka, also joined us and graced the occasion by launching the fourth version of the Cyber Crime Investigation Manual, the Report on Crypto Investigation, and CCITR's Annual Report. # CYBERSECURITY CENTRE OF EXCELLENCE (CCOE) Incubated 4 startups: - SpyVeil - Zarthcorp Tech - Hypermine - Phence With the objective to bridge the gap between academic conditions and industry requirements, CCoE signed MoUs with: - Malla Reddy Engineering College for Women - Vidya Jyothi Institute of Technology - RNS Institute of Technology, Bangalore - Trinity College of Engineering & Technology Karimnagar & Pedapalli (TCT-K&P) Engaged 3500+ professionals across key initiatives, including the DSCI-CCoE chapters meet, sessions at IDRBT and ASCI on advancing cybersecurity and privacy, and AI convergence for government scientists. Conducted a virtual walkthrough of the draft DPDP rules, trained professionals on Human Risk Management and Global AI regulations through the PrivSec spotlight, and hosted a workshop for CSGC2.0 (Cyber Security Grand Challenge). Concluded the Infosec University Hackathon, offering young talent employment, internship, and capability-building opportunities. Also held sessions with ASCI on “AI and Cybersecurity Convergence,” and an industry-focused session for NTPC on Cyber Jagrookta Diwas. Equipped 48 BBA students with the 2-credit course on “Cyber Sphere and Cybersecurity: A Global Concern” at IIFT, Kanikada campus. Concluded the March edition of PrivSec Spotlight on Hardware Security – Threats and Mitigations with 60+ participants. Write to us: media@dsci.in | www.dsci.in Data Security Council of India (DSCI), 4th Floor, Nasscom Campus, Plot No. 7-10, Sector 126, Noida, UP-201303

To further its objectives, DSCI engages with governments and their agencies, regulators, industry sectors, industry associations and think tanks for policy advocacy, thought leadership, capacity building and outreach activities. To strengthen thought leadership in cyber security and privacy, DSCI develops best practices and frameworks, publishes studies, surveys and papers. It builds capacity in security, privacy and cyber forensics through training and certification program for professionals and law enforcement agencies and engages stakeholders through various outreach initiatives including events, awards, chapters, consultations and membership programs. DSCI also endeavours to increase India’s share in the global security product and services market through global trade development initiatives. These aim to strengthen the security and privacy culture in India. ![DSCI Vision](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/vision.webp) ###### Vision To be the premier industry body for making cyberspace safe, secure and trusted. ![DSCI Vision](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/mission.webp) ###### Mission To make India a global leader in Cybersecurity and Privacy by harnessing opportunities of a thriving digital economy and to enhance India’s preparedness and capabilities for a safer, secure and trusted cyberspace. ###### Objectives ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-objectives-1.webp) Be trusted advisor to the Government in cybersecurity, privacy strategy, agenda setting and policy making in the country. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-objectives-2.webp) Scale outreach initiatives and events to the global level and widen collaboration, partnership and information exchange in the country. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-objectives-3.webp) Promote innovation & entrepreneurship to grow cyber security products and services industry globally and domestic market. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-objectives-4.webp) Develop cybersecurity community through initiatives arounds skill development (i.e., focussing on re-skilling & up-skilling) and awareness. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-objectives-5.webp) Help assess and promote maturity of organization and digital products through robust assurance ecosystem. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-objectives-6.webp) Scale the capabilities of the organization by attracting and nurturing talent. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-objectives-7.webp) Be global reference model for industry, national security and LEA partnership in scaling forensics and cybercrime investigation capabilities. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-objectives-8.webp) Build global credential program in security, privacy and forensics.

![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-strategy-2.webp) ##### Trust Build trust through policy advocacy and thought leadership ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/about-us-strategy-3.webp) ##### Collaboration Facilitate partnerships between government, academia and industry for optimising opportunities Access Exclusive Privileges and Transform Your Success. ###### Overview The DSCI Corporate Membership program offers a competitive and advantageous opportunity to member organizations by providing advisory support across varied topical themes relevant to industry sectors to strengthen the cyber security and data protection culture in India. With comprehensive membership benefits, organizations can constructively contribute to the vision of DSCI in making cyberspace safe, secure, and trusted. From opportunities in policy advocacy and thought leadership to outreach and awareness, DSCI provides members with a platform to learn, connect, voice, and strengthen perspectives Today, the DSCI Corporate Membership program includes large, medium, and small-sized organizations across the public and private sectors. Members represent the Banking, Oil & Energy, IT-BPM, Manufacturing, Telecom, Healthcare, Pharmaceuticals, Aviation, etc., along with Security and Privacy Services & Product Companies, Law firms, Consultancies, and others. ###### Membership Privileges ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/become-a-member-advisory.webp) ###### Advisory Consultation on queries and for implementation of DSCI Frameworks; cybercrime investigation and cyber forensics through Cyber Lab initiative ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/become-a-member-awareness.webp) ###### Awareness Receive updates on policies, practices and the latest in Data Protection and Security ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/become-a-member-development-of-standards.webp) ###### Development of standards Contribution to the development of international standards ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/become-a-member-global-trade-development.webp) ###### Global trade development Provide inputs and participate in bilateral and multilateral trade dialogues on global data flows and other issues ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/become-a-member-networking.webp) ###### Networking Connect to a global network of industry leaders, security professionals through eSecurity forums and DSCI Chapters ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/become-a-member-policy-advocacy.webp) ###### Policy advocacy Provide consultation and inputs for responding to government on policies related to cybersecurity, privacy, cloud, internet governance, cyber forensics and others ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/become-a-member-publications-updates.webp) ###### Publications & updates Subscription to DSCI Security Framework (DSF©), DSCI Privacy Framework (DPF©), DSCI Assessment Framework for Security and & Privacy (DAF-S©) & (DAF-P©) and globally acknowledged study materials, Surveys and Reports ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/become-a-member-branding-and-visibility.webp) ###### Branding and visibility Build your organizational brand, leadership and enhance visibility through our events, awards, website, blog and social media platforms ### How to Enroll #### Step 1 ##### Complete Online Form Complete the online Corporate Membership form and we will register your membership request.

#### Step 2 ##### Nominate the Head Nominate the Head of Information Security (CISO/CSO/CIO/CPO) or any other appropriate dignitary to be the touch point with DSCI for all Security and Privacy related services. #### Step 3 ##### Pay the Fees Pay the membership fees (Online/Cheque/DD drawn in favor of "Data Security Council of India" payable at New Delhi). Upon confirmation, we will send you the membership login details. #### Structure of Corporate membership (2024-25) [Register Now](https://dsci.glueup.com/) Category 1 ##### Turnover >=100 Crores ###### ₹ 3,00,000 + GST (as applicable) Category 2 ##### Turnover 10-99crs ###### ₹ 1,00,000 + GST (as applicable) Category 3 ##### Turnover < 10 crs ###### ₹ 40,000 + GST (as applicable) Category 4 ##### Turnover < 1Cr and <= 3 years of incorporation ###### ₹ 10,000 + GST (as applicable) Category 5 ##### Institutions ###### Customised (Write to membership@dsci.in for details) ### Member Exclusive ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/DPF-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/DSF-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/FAQs-on-IT-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/NASSCOM-DSCI-Feedback-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/DPF-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/DSF-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/FAQs-on-IT-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/NASSCOM-DSCI-Feedback-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/DPF-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/DSF-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/FAQs-on-IT-min.webp) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/NASSCOM-DSCI-Feedback-min.webp) PreviousNext * 1 * 2 * 3 * 4 ### Over 500+ Members When you become a DSCI corporate member, you pledge to build a culture of security & privacy in your organization. Others [Member Directory](https://www.dsci.in/corporate-member/member-directory) ### Frequently Asked Questions ## Q. What is the DSCI Corporate Membership program ? DSCI offers its Corporate Membership program to organizations across industry sectors, which wish to build a strong Cyber Security architecture within their organizations and work towards making Cyber Security a board-level agenda. DSCI provides insights into latest threats, best practices, security solutions, and expert advice for data protection, in its workshops, roundtables and seminars. Corporate members also receive a monthly newsletter on important topical issues in the domains security and privacy relevant to their industry. ## Q. Who are eligible for DSCI Corporate Membership ? Organizations representing any sector are eligible to apply for the DSCI Corporate Membership Program. Current DSCI Corporate members include large, medium and small sized organizations from IT-BPM, Public sector, Banking, Manufacturing, Telecom, Security providers, Consulting Organizations, Institutes and Law firms, to name a few. ## Q. Can I apply for Corporate Membership, if I am an individual? How is the DSCI corporate membership different from DSCI individual membership ? No. The DSCI Corporate Membership Program is open for registered organizations and institutes. As an individual, you can join a DSCI Chapter in your nearest city. Our Corporate Membership Program is exclusively for organizations that wish to associate with DSCI in their organizational capacity whereas individual memberships is for individuals who wish to play an active role in their DSCI regional chapters across twelve cities in India. ## Q. How can I check my category for Corporate Membership and entitled fee structure ? There are four categories on the basis of the organization size. The fee structure is different for each of the categories. [Know more](https://www.dsci.in/content/become-member#register) ## Q. What kind of benefits my organization will be entitled to ? Benefits are different for each of the categories. For more details on, benefits please write to membership[at]dsci[dot]in with the category of your organization. ## Q. Do I need to fill some form to register for becoming a corporate membership ? Both online and offline registrations are accepted. For Online Registration fill up the form. Offline registration form can be requested by mailing membership[at]dsci[dot]in ## Q. What is the fee structure of nasscom members ? nasscom members can obtain DSCI Corporate membership free of charge. ## Q. nasscom members and non-NASSCOM members ? Non-nasscom membership will have to pay according as per the fee structure ## Q. When will I receive the membership e-mail after registration? What if I don’t receive an e-mail ? You will receive a system generated mail immediately after you have registered for the membership.

content: In case you don’t receive any e-mail, please write to membership[at]dsci[dot]in ## Q. Will I be receiving the membership number and login ID ? Yes, login ID and password are sent to the registered email IDs once the organization membership payment is received by DSCI. Incase login ID is not received within 72 hours (working days) of the payment, organization are requested to write to membership[at]dsci[dot]in ## Q. How can I change contact details as an existing member ? You can change and add/edit contact details by logging in with the Login ID and password provided by the primary contact. ## Q .Who should be the primary contact to interface with DSCI for privacy related activities / services ? It is advisable to nominate the Head of Information Security (CISO/CSO/CIO/CPO) or any other appropriate senior executive from your organization, to interface with DSCI. Head of Frauds/ Cybercrime Investigation, Chief Vigilance Officers can also be nominated. ## Q. Will I be receiving the membership number and login ID ? Yes, login ID and password are sent to the registered email IDs once the organization membership payment is received by DSCI. Incase login ID is not received within 72 hours (working days) of the payment, organization are requested to write to membership[at]dsci[dot]in ## Q. What is the tenure of the corporate membership ? The membership will be valid for twelve months and will begin from the first day of the successive month of DSCI receiving the membership fee. ## Q. What happens if I don’t pay the membership fees ? Your organization’s name will be removed from the membership list. A mail regarding this will be sent to the registered email ID. ## Q. When is the invoice received ? Once the payment is receive, an e-mail communication will be sent to the organization with the invoice. This will be done within a week after DSCI receives the payment. A hard copy of the invoice will be sent to at the registered address as provided in contact details. ## Q. How can I modify the details of my organization? Can I modify the details of the contact person ? You can modify the details anytime by accessing the DSCI Corporate Membership portal and logging in with the login ID and password as provided to your organization. ## Q. Will I be getting a membership certificate? What will be its validity ? You will receive the membership certificate from DSCI. It will be valid for one year, beginning the successive month from the date of membership. ## Q. What are the statutory benefits to a member organization ? As a DSCI Corporate Member, you are eligible to attend DSCI Annual General Meetings. ## Q. I am changing my organization. What do I need to do ? You can simply drop us a mail notifying us about the same, along with your membership number and the contact details of the individual whom we can connect to for future communications. ## Q. Besides becoming a corporate member, how else can to contribute to DSCI **You can choose to:** Become a [Chapter Member](https://www.dsci.in/chapter-registration)Nominate/suggest a colleague to undergo training as [DCPP](https://www.dsci.in/content/dsci-certified-privacy-professional-dcpp)Write for our [blog](https://www.dsci.in/blogs/) ## Q. I wish to discontinue my membership. How do I do it ? Write to membership[at]dsci[dot]in stating the reason for discontinuance and we shall contact you. DSCI is committed to being the leading voice in privacy protection. To that end, we have convened the DSCI Privacy Leadership Forum to bring together privacy leaders in a common forum to enable privacy preparedness of the industry. The forum shall meet periodically to deliberate on issues that are of importance to the privacy concerns of the industry. Leaders of the forum shall work in sub-committees or as part of special interest groups in order to cover the many thematic areas of interest. ### Objectives of the Forum ##### 1 Collectively deliberate on the latest privacy policy, regulatory, and technological developments across the globe ##### 2 Have meaningful exchanges on the core set of challenges organizations might be facing in Privacy implementation and ways to surmount them ##### 3 Drive readiness of organizations and sectors from the standpoint of the upcoming Privacy legislation in the country ##### 4 Promote best practices and measures for making Privacy a key differentiator ##### 5 Get across the larger Industry concerns to the authorities ##### 6 Work towards the development of industry code of practices ### Special Interest Groups(SIGs) Privacy by Design Data Transfers Employee Data Privacy Privacy Maturity Modelling Privacy Impact Assessment ### Publications [![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/knowledge-centre/2024/DPLF-whitepaper-thumbnail.webp)](https://www.dsci.in/resource/content/privacy-due-diligence) ### ![](https://www.dsci.in/assets/img/date 1.svg) Nov 08, 2024 The ‘Privacy Due Diligence: A Practical Guide for Data Protection Impact Assessments’ guide provides a comprehensive framework for conducting Data Protection Impact Assessments (DPIAs) to manage privacy risks associ... The committee is comprised of accomplished professionals with extensive experience in public sector units. The committee aims to drive excellence by sharing best practices and guidelines with end users, technology deliberations with solution providers, policy and framework engagement with regulators for a holistic cyber driven ecosystem. Through collaborative efforts and strategic initiatives, our committee endeavors to elevate cyber resilience across critical and manufacturing sectors, safeguarding national interests and fostering digital trust and innovation. ### Objectives #### Facilitate Best Practices Curate and disseminate industry-leading cyber security practices tailored for critical and manufacturing sectors. #### Regulatory Engagement Act as a liaison between industry stakeholders and regulatory bodies to ensure compliance and foster a conducive regulatory environment. #### End-User Advocacy Champion end-user needs by promoting cyber awareness, education, and user-centric security solutions. #### Ecosystem Collaboration Foster partnerships among practitioners, solution providers, academia, and government agencies to create a robust cyber security ecosystem. #### Sector-Specific Initiatives Develop tailored initiatives addressing unique challenges faced by critical and manufacturing sectors in their digital transformation journey. ### Focus Areas ##### **Critical Infrastructure Protection** Safeguarding essential services such as power, energy, manufacturing, transportation, and healthcare from cyber threats. ##### **Industrial Control Systems (ICS) Security** Ensuring the security and resilience of manufacturing processes and control systems. ##### **Supply Chain Security** Mitigating risks associated with third-party dependencies and strengthening supply chain resilience. ##### **Data Privacy and Confidentiality** Upholding data privacy standards and protecting sensitive information from unauthorized access. ##### **Incident Response and Crisis Management** Enhancing capabilities to detect, respond to, and recover from cyber incidents effectively. ###### Committee Members * ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2025/aseem-mukhi.webp) ### Aseem Mukhi Head cyber security, Renew Energy * ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2025/liton-nandy-1.webp) ### Liton Nandy * ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2025/mihir-joshi.webp) ### Mihir Joshi CISO, Tata Power * ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2025/paparaju.webp) ### Paparaju Buddhavarapu Aseem Mukhi heads cybersecurity at ReNew, a leading decarbonization solutions company focused on accelerating the transition to renewable energy. At ReNew, he manages enterprise security, data protection, and Operational Technology (OT) cybersecurity. His extensive background spans vital sectors including power and utilities, BFSI, telecommunications, government, and law enforcement, providing a unique perspective on diverse security challenges.

In his professional journey, Aseem has been instrumental in developing nationally significant cybersecurity engagements as well as sectoral projects, focusing on security strategy, policy, risk assessment, security operations, and cyber resilience. Beyond his organizational role, Aseem is a recognized Subject Matter Expert (SME), contributing to initiatives like validation of Nasscom Sector Skill Council's National Qualification Packs for Cybersecurity. He also actively participates in cybersecurity skill development as a member of the technical subcommittee at CDAC Hyderabad. Liton Nandy is a seasoned IT veteran and a Digital Transformation Expert & Evangelist who brings over 36+ years of industry experience. With a successful tenure as the former CIO and Country Head of Digital-IT at IndianOil, he has spearheaded many groundbreaking technology initiatives for Public Sector Enterprises and the Government sector. Liton's experience and expertise span across various domains, including Digital Transformation and Enablement, Strategic Thinking in Cybersecurity, Tech-Business Connect Management, Innovation Incubation/Management, Cybersecurity Readiness Planning, Software Development, CX/CSAT Enhancement, Change Management, and Talent and Skill Development. He is adept at bridging the gap between technology and business, leading and deriving values from digital innovations, managing complex and large projects, driving change, and nurturing collaboration across teams by overcoming complex barriers. Some of his key achievements include leading large-scale Enterprise Digital Business Projects in the Oil & Gas space such as CLDP (Common LPG Data Platform), DBTL (Direct Benefit Transfer of LPG), and PMUY (Pradhan Mantri Ujjwala Yojana) bringing in transformative impact towards efficient automation, ease of doing business, and enhanced satisfaction of citizens of India, leading ERP and DMS-CRM-Loyalty projects for Oil & Gas Organization to support large scale supply chain and customer delivery system, operationalizing a comprehensive Enterprise Content Management System (ECMS), developing large and integrated retail and terminal automation system, implementing robust Cyber Security ecosystem & Data Governance framework, and instilling a digital mindset in business partners. Liton excels in formulating and executing strategies for Digital Transformation and Cybersecurity, IT Policy Formulation, IT Audit & Security Assessments, Data Governance, Business Analytics, Change Management & User Adoption. His industry expertise and leadership have enabled him to drive impactful changes and deliver quality solutions for customers while empowering and developing high-performing IT teams. Mihir Joshi is a seasoned Chief Information Security Officer with deep expertise in securing critical infrastructure within the power and energy sector. With over 17 years of experience, he leads enterprise-wide cybersecurity initiatives focused on Operational Technology (OT) and IT convergence, regulatory compliance and resilience against evolving cyber threats. Known for fostering strong cross-functional collaboration, Mihir Joshi drives risk-based strategies that protect grid reliability and support digital transformation in the energy ecosystem. Before Joining Tata Power Company Limited, Mihir Joshi has served as a Global CISO in a crypto currency firm and CISO in financial services, mutual funds and insurance sector. With a focus on proactive threat detection, fraud prevention, and customer data protection, Mihir Joshi leads high-performing security teams and advises executive leadership on cybersecurity strategy aligned with business growth and regulatory expectations. He is also serving as a "Cyber Security Advisor" at VDA's and Cryptocurrency Exchanges. He has been speaker at various events like BlackHat, GISEC, DSCI and CxO forums. Paparaju Buddhavarapu is a distinguished cybersecurity expert having near four decades of experience with a remarkable 39-year stint at ONGC. With a robust background in enterprise cybersecurity, he has served in pivotal roles, notably as Chief Information Security Officer (CISO) at ONGC Ltd and ONGC Videsh Limited, Head – Operational Technology , Head-SCADA etc. He has been a critical leader in Operations & Maintenance of the Security Operations Centre, SCADA, Threat Mitigation, Capacity Building, Phishing and Smishing. In addition, he is proficient in Vulnerability Assessment and Mitigation, Risk Analysis and Mitigation, Information Security and Management System, and Data Centre Audit. Excellence in developing cyber resilience and awareness, business continuity, and mastering root cause analysis are a few of the many areas of his prowess. He is an eminent leader in handling project management, contract management, and policy creation.

He has also fostered the IT and OT technologies of the Upstream Oil and Gas industry, where he facilitated the Operations & Management of Process Instrumentation and Enterprise Access Control Systems, Gas Turbine Control Systems, Distributed Control Systems, Programmable Logic Controllers, Seismic Data Acquisition systems, IT systems, and PBX systems. Paparaju's educational background includes an advanced management program from IIM Kolkata and a graduate degree in Electronics and Communication Engineering from Jawaharlal Nehru Technological University. [Home](https://www.dsci.in/content/data-protection-framework-india) / Data Protection Framework for India #### Data Protection Framework for India #### ![](https://www.dsci.in/assests/img/date 1.svg)March 5, 2025 ##### Summary of DSCI Feedback on draft DPDP Rules 2025 The Data Security Council of India (DSCI) has provided feedback on India's draft Digital Personal Data Protection Rules, 2025, appreciating the principle-based approach while offering targeted recommendations to improve clarity and implementation feasibility. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp) [Summary of DSCI Feedback on draft DPDP Rules 2025](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2025/Summary_DSCI-MeitY-Submission-draft-DPDP-Rules.pdf) [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2025/Summary_DSCI-MeitY-Submission-draft-DPDP-Rules.pdf) #### ![](https://www.dsci.in/assests/img/date 1.svg) January 9, 2025 ##### Summary of draft DPDP Rules 2025 On 3rd January 2025, the Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology published the Draft Digital Personal Data Protection Rules 2025 for public consultation. This document is intended to provide a high-level summary of the noteworthy details that have been introduced through the draft Rules to the data protection framework in India. It is important to note that these provisions are undergoing public consultation and will only be considered binding law after final notification in the Gazette. For detailed information on the provisions of the rules, see the official full text of the rules [here](https://static.mygov.in/innovateindia/2025/01/03/mygov-999999999568142946.pdf) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp) [Summary of draft DPDP Rules 2025](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2025/Draft-DPDP-Rules-2025-DSCI-Summary.pdf) [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2025/Draft-DPDP-Rules-2025-DSCI-Summary.pdf) #### ![](https://www.dsci.in/assests/img/date 1.svg) October 5, 2023 ##### Decoding the Digital Personal Data Protection Act 2023 for Citizens and Businesses The DPDP Act proposes to grant individuals certain rights, including the right to have their personal data processed only with their consent, and it also includes provisions for measures to safeguard their data. This comprehensive act seeks to find a balance between protecting the rights of individuals and meeting the data processing needs of businesses. To concisely convey its essence, detailed infographics have been created, outlining the core principles and provisions of the Act. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp) [Decoding the Digital Personal Data Protection Act 2023 for Citizens](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/DPDP-Act-Citizens.pdf) [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/DPDP-Act-Citizens.pdf) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp) [Decoding the Digital Personal Data Protection Act 2023 for Businesses](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/DPDP-Act-2023-Business.pdf) [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/DPDP-Act-2023-Business.pdf) #### ![](https://www.dsci.in/assests/img/date 1.svg) August 11, 2023 ##### Summary – The Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023 On 3rd August 2023, the Digital Personal Data Protection (DPDP) Bill, 2023 was introduced in the Lok Sabha and passed on 9th August 2023, and subsequently introduced and passed on 9th August 2023 in the Rajya Sabha.

On 11th August 2023, the President of India gave assent to the bill and henceforth known as the Digital Personal Data Protection (DPDP) Act, 2023. The Act shall come into force on such date as the Central Government may, by notification in the Official Gazette, appoint and different dates may be appointed for different provisions of this Act. Below is the copy of the Act as published by ‘The Gazette of India’ and a brief chapter-wise summary of the provisions of the DPDP Act 2023 along with a comparison with the 2022 Draft Bill of the same. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp) [The Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/The%20Digital%20Personal%20Data%20Protection%20Act%2C%202023.pdf) [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/The%20Digital%20Personal%20Data%20Protection%20Act%2C%202023.pdf) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp) [Summary - The Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/DSCI%20Summary-DPDP%20Act%2C%202023.pdf) [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/DSCI%20Summary-DPDP%20Act%2C%202023.pdf) #### ![](https://www.dsci.in/assests/img/date 1.svg) August 3, 2023 ##### Digital Personal Data Protection Bill 2023 The Digital Personal Data Protection Bill 2023 has been formally introduced in the Indian Parliament’s Lok Shabha. It is a concrete step forward in India’s journey towards establishing a comprehensive data protection regime. The Bill brings forth some key changes when contrasted against the 2022 draft. The clause on deemed consent has been removed and in its place certain legitimate uses have been prescribed for processing of personal data. Additionally, cross-border data transfers have been eased with the Government having the power to notify countries to which transfers will be restricted. Some clarity has also been provided on the operational functioning of the Data Protection Board. The complete contents of the bill can be found [here](https://sansad.in/getFile/BillsTexts/LSBillTexts/Asintroduced/113_2023_LS_Eng83202330313PM.pdf?source=legislation). Watch out for DSCI's comprehensive summary of the bill to be out soon! ##### Digital Personal Data Protection Bill 2022 The Ministry of Electronics and IT (MeitY) has notified the draft Digital Personal Data Protection Bill 2022 (DPDPB, 2022) on 18th November 2022. The scope of the bill applies to automated processing of personal data which is either collected from Data Principals online or personal data which is collected offline but is digitised. Non-personal data and anonymised data have been omitted from the scope of the law. The complete script of the draft bill can be accessed [here](https://www.meity.gov.in/writereaddata/files/The%20Digital%20Personal%20Data%20Potection%20Bill%2C%202022_0.pdf). Below is a brief chapter-wise summary of the proposed legislation along with a comparison with the JPC Report and Personal Data Protection Bill 2021. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp)Digital Personal Data Protection Bill 2022 [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/DSCI-Summary-of-DPDPB-2022.pdf) ##### Summary| Report of Joint Committee on The Personal Data Protection Bill, 2019 The Joint Parliamentary Committee chaired by Member of Parliament Shri P.P. Chaudhary tabled the report (access here) on the Data Protection Bill before both houses of parliament on the 16th of December 2021. The document comprises two parts, the first of which is the report with general observations and the second is the amended Bill with clause-by-clause recommendations of the committee. Some key recommendations are as follows: * The new legislation will deal with personal and non-personal data both * Government asked to follow a timeline for phased implementation of Data Protection Act * Government asked to bring mirror copy of the sensitive and critical data from abroad and do localization. * Policy to be prepared and pronounced for Gradual data localization recommended. * Government asked to establish a mechanism for certification of all digital and IOT devices. * Social media platforms to be treated as publishers and be regulated for the content they host. * Reporting of Breach of personal data within specific time. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp)Summary and Primer on Joint Parliamentary Committee Report and Data Protection Bill, 2021 [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/Summary- and-Primer-on-Joint-Parliamentary-Committee-Report-and-Data-Protection-Bill-2021.pdf) ##### DSCI Feedback on Draft NPD Committee Report Data Security Council of India (DSCI) shared it’s submission to the Non-Personal Data Committee, on the draft recommendations put forth in the report by the Committee of Experts on Non-Personal Data Governance Framework.

DSCI conducted industry consultations to assess the likely impact on the Industry of the proposed recommendations and these have informed our assessment of the report. DSCI Submission highlighted the key principles to be taken into consideration, while envisioning a data sharing mechanism for Non-personal data in India, keeping in mind India’s Digital economy growth charter and also to reinforce India’s global position as a growing digital hub and innovation. It also raised, certain issues that subsist within the framework proposed by the committee, and has urged the committee to revaluate the assertions and recommendations put forth in the report with respect to its interplay with the upcoming Personal Data Protection Law in India and other established regulations with respect to intellectual property rights and competition.. The following key concerns were addressed in our submission coupled with recommendations to address them: * Objective and narrative of the report, w.r.t data utilisation * Requiring Individual’s consent for Anonymisation and usage of Anonymised data * Definition of Non-Personal Data- Public, Private and Community * Sensitivity of Non-Personal Data and restrictions on data flows * Role of stakeholders- Data Custodians and Non-Personal Data Authority ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp)DSCI Feedback on Draft NPD Committee Report [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/DSCI Feedback on Draft NPD Committee Report.pdf) ##### Member Consultation on Non-Personal Data Governance Framework The Committee on Non-Personal Data has sought comments on its draft recommendation laid down in its report titled _'Report by the Committee of Experts on Non-Personal Data Governance Framework'_ ( available [here](https://static.mygov.in/rest/s3fs-public/mygov_159453381955063671.pdf)) by **August 13, 2020**. (Notice for feedback available [here](https://www.mygov.in/task/share-your-inputs-draft-non-personal-data-governance-framework/).) The committee under the chairmanship of Kris Gopalakrishnan (Co-Founder, Infosys) with the mandate of studying various issues relating to Non-Personal Data and to make specific suggestions for consideration of the Central Government on regulation of Non-Personal Data, has put forth these recommendations in said report for public consultation. The recommendations of the report have been summarised in the document. You may please download the file below. Data Security Council of India, would be submitting its comments to the committee. To enable us to formulate a robust and representative submission we request you to share your inputs on these draft recommendations with us at membership[at]dsci[dot]in or anand[dot]krishnan[at]dsci[dot]in by **3rd August (Monday), 2020**. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp)DSCI Consultation Draft Non-Personal Data Committe Report [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/DSCI-Consultation-Draft-Non-Personal-Data-Committe-Report.pdf) ##### Personal Data Protection (PDP) Bill 2019 - Key Highlights The Personal Data Protection (PDP) Bill 2019, which was cleared by the Union Cabinet last week, was introduced in the Lok Sabha on Wednesday, December 11, 2019, by Shri Ravi Shankar Prasad, the Minister of Electronics and Information Technology, Government of India. The bill seeks to provide for the protection of personal data of individuals and establishes a Data Protection Authority for the same. The bill is referred to a Joint Select Committee comprising of members from Lok Sabha and Rajya Sabha. We would wish to get your views and suggestions on the bill. We request you to kindly share the inputs with DSCI at membership[at]dsci[dot]in latest by Saturday, December 21, 2019, to enable us to provide an industry submission to the Joint Parliamentary Committee and MeitY. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp)Personal Data Protection (PDP) Bill 2019 - Key Highlights [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/Personal_Data_Protection_Bill_2019_The_Key_Highlights.pdf) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp)Summary & Key Changes [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/NASSCOM-DSCI_Consulation_PDP_Bill2019.pdf) ##### Protection of Personal Data Bill, 2018- NASSCOM-DSCI Member Consultation Ministry of electronics and information technology has opened the Protection of Personal Data Bill, 2018 for public consultation.**The deadline for submission of responses is 10th September 2018. The Bill can be accessed here:[Personal Data Bill, 2018 ](http://www.meity.gov.in/writereaddata/files/Personal_Data_Protection_Bill%2C2018_0.pdf)** NASSCOM-DSCI will be submitting a comprehensive response. **Please share your inputs on anand.krishnan@dsci.in by 1st September 2018.** Questionnaire to share your position on critical impact areas for industry and provision wise comments is enclosed.

A presentation summarising the provisions and the issues has also been enclosed for your reference. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp)Protection of Personal Data Bill, 2018 Questionnaire [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/Protection%20of%20Personal%20Data%20Bill%2C%202018%20Questionnaire.docx) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp)Protection of Personal Data Bill, 2018 [](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2023/Protection of Personal Data Bill%2C 2018.pdf) Government of India has constituted a Committee of Experts (nine member) under the chairmanship of Justice B N Srikrishna to study various issues related to data protection and develop a Data Protection Framework for India. A [White Paper on Data Protection ](http://meity.gov.in/writereaddata/files/white_paper_on_data_protection_in_india_171127_final_v2.pdf) Framework was released by Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology (MeitY) earlier for public comments. Subsequently, the committee conducted several consultation meetings with stakeholders and solicited inputs on the whitepaper. The final draft of [Personal Data Protection Bill, 2018](http://meity.gov.in/content/personal-data-protection-bill-2018) alongside the Expert committee report was submitted to the government on 27 July 2018. DSCI CEO one of the members in the nine-member committee has been participating and providing inputs to the committee deliberations. Earlier in January DSCI-NASSCOM made a combined submission on the whitepaper to MeitY. DSCI has prepared an overview document capturing the key aspects of the proposed Bill for easy reference. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/2023/pdf-icon_0.webp)DSCI Highlights on Personal Data Protection Register at the link [here](https://forms.office.com/pages/responsepage.aspx?id=Ans1OLE11U6ad2cQ3vCILcHxrzmGVNxKqyIQ_MO6ZfNUNENRVktTWFVYM0RVVURITFc2STYzR0xOUS4u&route=shorturl) **_(Terms and Conditions apply)_** # About CyberShikshaa DSCI in partnership with Microsoft and in support with Information Security Education and Awareness (ISEA) of Ministry of Electronics & IT (MeitY) launched CyberShikshaa in September 2018. The CyberShikshaa flagship program '**Cyber Security Training Program** ' trains women engineering graduates from tier-II, tier-III cities and rural areas in the niche field of Cyber Security. C-DAC, NIELIT and our other premier training partners conduct the online/offline training sessions. In 2021, after a successful run of the initial Cyber Security Training Program, '**Privacy Module for Women on Break** ' was rolled out for women professionals who are on career break due to medical, personal or any other reasons and want to make a career in Data Privacy. This is a pioneer credentialing program which equips women professionals with necessary skills to advance their careers in the growing field of Data Privacy. Both CyberShikshaa programs entail placement assistance for the candidates. Additionally, a self-learning '**CyberShikshaa Fundamentals** ' program was also launched to introduce cyber security concepts to college students. ![CyberShikshaa Coffee Table Book](https://www.dsci.in/cyber-shikshaa/assets/images/cybershikshaa-coffee-table-book.webp) [Read the Success Stories](https://www.dsci.in/cyber-shikshaa/assets/report/CyberShikshaa-Coffee-Table-Book.pdf) Previous ![quote](https://www.dsci.in/cyber-shikshaa/assets/images/icons/quote.svg) Cybersecurity is more than securing systems; it's a horizon of career opportunities. The CyberShikshaa programme by DSCI and Microsoft empowers women with industry-ready skills for the challenging but rewarding field of cybersecurity and privacy. We encourage more stakeholders to join the movement and support women talent in the cybersecurity domain. Total number of candidates taking online training since then is close to 300. 04 A strong corpus of 80+ recruiters from across the tech industry have hired and trained students for different roles. 05 1000+ candidates have completed CyberShikshaa Security Training program with a placement rate of 60%.

06 100 women who were on a career break have been trained for DCPP certification under CyberShikshaa Privacy Module for 'Women on Break'. 07 4,660 students from 28 academic institutions of India have However, they often grapple with questions around privacy, security, compliance, availability and breach. With a bid to drive broader Cloud adoption and to comprehensively address the apprehensions pertaining to Security & Privacy on the Cloud, DSCI has conceptualized the 'Secure with Cloud' initiative. This program aims to understand key drivers, challenges associated with cloud adoption and develop evidence-based deliberations.

![ ](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/page/2024/priview-banner.webp) #### PriView- Privacy Notice Generator A fundamental pillar of data protection and privacy is ‘transparency’. To ensure transparency of their data processing practices, organisations should inform their customers and users about how their personal data will be collected and used to provide them access to digital products and services. Transparency about how businesses handle personal data also ensures that users are able to provide meaningful consent and exercise genuine control over their personal data. With the enactment of the Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023 (DPDPA) in India, the requirement for a privacy notice and request for consent has been formalized under the law. Upon the enforcement of the DPDPA, this requirement will become a legal compliance expected of businesses in the public and private sectors. To facilitate compliance with this requirement, and as a foundational step towards improving privacy awareness and maturity of businesses, DSCI and Privy by IDfy have collaborated on developing (_PriView- A comprehensive privacy notice generator_). The tool is intended to provide a free -of-cost, accessible, intuitive, and self-guided starter kit to help you create a customized reference template for your business or organisation’s privacy notice in a few simple steps. ###### Who is it for? The tool can be used by privacy professionals, data protection officers, CTOs, CISOs, etc. in any organization or business seeking to create a privacy notice informing their users or customers about the purposes for which they process personal data and the kind of personal data they collect. In particular organisations that are starting out on their data protection compliance journey in India would benefit from referring to the notice generated by the tool as a base template which can be amended as needed. This could include: Startups MSMEs Public sector undertakings Other digital native businesses ###### How does PriView work? The tool provides two channels for creation of your organisation’s customized privacy notice #### Create your privacy notice manually If your organization does not currently have a comprehensive privacy policy, you can create your privacy notice in a few simple steps with this option. The user can manually select the applicable industry sector and the corresponding purposes relevant to the digital product/service/journey for which the notice is intended. The tool will then create an editable privacy notice based on the data input by the user. #### Create your privacy notice using existing privacy policy If your organization already has a comprehensive privacy policy, you can create a digital product/service/journey specific notice using this option. Upon selecting the relevant industry sector and uploading the existing privacy policy of your organization, the algorithms underpinning the tool analyze your existing privacy policy to extract data processing activities and identify personal data collected to generate a customised and editable notice. [Try PriView Now](https://priview.idfy.com/notice-generator) To download the PriView Information Guide and to know how it works [_click here_](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/documents/2024/PriView-Information-Guide.pdf) **Disclaimer:-**_Please note that clicking on the link above to use the privacy notice generator tool will redirect you to IDfy’s website and digital platform. DSCI is not liable for the technical maintenance and functioning of the tool. DSCI also does not process or store any data that is input on the tool for creation of the notice. This tool is for general informative and awareness purposes to facilitate foundational steps towards good privacy practices. It is not intended to guarantee legal compliance to the DPDPA or other applicable laws. This tool should not be relied upon as a substitute for specific legal or other professional advice. Legal advice should always be sought before taking any action based on the information provided. It is the responsibility of the user of this tool to ensure proper vetting of the notice generated before utilising the same for their digital products and services. This tool is currently in its first iteration and will undergo continuous improvement based on feedback and internal assessment._ ![logo](https://www.dsci.in/files/logos/DSCI-White-1.svg) Operational Office – 4th Floor, NASSCOM Campus, Plot No.

# DSCI Privacy Assessment (DAF©) ###### Security (DAF-S) Security as a subject and organization function has been expanding its scope and reach, which is articulated by DSF© in 16 distinct disciplines. Maturity of each discipline is becoming important for effective delivering objectives of security. Ever increasing complexity of the underlying infrastructure, extending nature of the business ecosystem, growing pace of adopting new technology solutions and innovative ways of connecting and accessing IT assets are increasingly organizations to evolving, advanced, persistent and targeted security threats. Managing the affairs of security is becoming more daunting, demanding and granular. A weakness, lacuna and deficiency in one area may lead to catastrophic damage the organization’s security. So maturity of security in each of the disciplines is becoming important for the overall maturity of the security. Secondly, competence in the specific disciplines such as − application security, threat and vulnerability management, monitoring & incident management and data security − are becoming critical to the performance of security in delivering a swift response to the security threats and protection of the critical information assets. Assessment of these disciplines for their competence, role, efforts, and performance would provide critical insight into an organization’s capability of delivering to the desired security expectations. DSCI Assessment Framework for Security (DAF-S)© is developed on the premise of discipline based approach to security. Discipline specific security assessment solves many problems and challenges associated with assessment of security. Many of the contemporary methods fails on account of Ability to reach realities of security, Relevancy to the evolution of the subject, challenges & trends and Dynamism to incorporate or reflect the changes & evolutions. DSCI Assessment Framework – Security focuses on Bringing Reality, Relevance and Dynamism in Security Assessments. ### Key features ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/strategy-1.png) #### Reality Reach to the granularity of practices Reveals deficiencies at architectural and technology competence level Detect gaps in the coverage of the programs and initiatives Identify gaps in the arrangements set up for integrating capabilities Discover issues in the process design Find inefficiency of operational elements ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/strategy-1.png) #### Relevance Focus on contemporary approaches, technical evolutions, and trends associated with a specific discipline Compile strategic options, tactical steps & operational practices evolving around the discipline, and benchmarking the organizational practices against them Derive methods of evaluating and benchmarking organizational practices ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/strategy-1.png) #### Dynamism Build continuously improving knowledge base around DSF© Introduce the modular and adaptive approach for assessment to incorporate changes Enhance competence of assessors and auditors through continual skills and knowledge improvements Establish a collaboration mechanism for sharing of knowledge, learningg & experiences ### Security Assessment using:: (DAF-S) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp)**Assessment Objectives:** DSF© provides a set of maturity metrics for each of the disciplines. They articulate the objectives an assessment should look at while assessing practices in a specific discipline. Each of the parameters is elaborated as expectations and capabilities that an organization should deliver in order to improve its maturity in the discipline. The assessment objectives and the respective elaboration provide broad guidelines and directions for conducting the assessment. Auditor or assessor should take a careful note of these objectives outlined at the start of each discipline. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp)**Assessment Areas:** Each discipline organizes the assessment questionnaire in 4 to 5 assessment areas. These areas resemble the competence that an organization needs to enhance to improve its maturity. From the perspective of assessment, an organization’s performance in a specific discipline can be derived by evaluating its performance in these areas. Secondly, these areas may become measurement parameters in a measurement scheme that may evolve around the (DAF-S)©. The total 71 competence areas in the 16 disciplines will help an organization provide a high level picture of the state of security, with an opportunity to drill down to a specific competence areas. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp)**Assessment Questionnaire:** (DAF-S)© provides a detailed evaluation questionnaire for each of the disciplines, organized under the assessment areas.

content: The assessment questionnaire provides aspects, dimensions, and characteristics need to be evaluated in judging the competence in a specific discipline. To satisfy the objective behind a specific question, an auditor should adopt various methods such as developing information filing forms, interview to understand the dimensions & perspectives, field visit for observations and collecting the evidences and conduct a technical assessment if required. The objectives, areas and questionnaire provided by (DAF-S)© can serve the purpose of doing self-assessment, provided that the one doing the assessment is familiar with all perspectives, dimensions and aspects of conducting the assessment. Additionally, DSCI will empanel the assessors for conducting the assessment and Organizations may avail services of these assessors to perform third party assessment. The assessors will be extensively trained and certified by DSCI, to allow them perform the third party audits. The organizations intend to conduct self-assessment may like to train and certify their resources to carry the discipline specific assessment. DSCI will make specific arrangements for managing the Assessment requests. This will entail managing of assessment request, working with empaneled auditors, managing the assessment reports and results, etc. ### Privacy (DAF-P©) In 2012, the DSCI Assessment Framework-Privacy (DAF-P©) was published to help organizations provide assurance to external stakeholders on the implementation of a privacy program based on DPF©. These frameworks have been utilized and referred by many organizations across industry sectors. It consists of two parts, with each focusing on distinct aspects of privacy implementation – one focuses on Assessment of Organizational Competence in Privacy based on practice areas defined in DPF© while the other – Privacy Principles based Assessment focuses on implementation of global privacy principles. The first part is based on the nine practice areas listed under DPF© and the assessment questionnaire is thus designed to help organizations assess and mature their privacy program. The questionnaire is based on the practices defined in DPF©, with suggestive guidance parameters to aid the assessors when conducting assessments. The assessment could be conducted in either modes: Self-Assessment or External Assessment. The external assessment through DSCI empanelled auditors could help organizations attain DSCI Certification. The second part is intended to help organizations assess and improve maturity in the implementation of global privacy principles across all the organizational processes that deal with personal information and in the process optimize their efforts while implementing privacy principles across global operations. To address the specific needs of the organizations having operations in India, this part of the (DAF-P)© also contains an assessment questionnaire that has been designed to help assess compliance against the privacy principles prescribed under section 43A of the IT (Amendment) Act, 2008. This part of the (DAF-P)© is intended for self-assessment only and, for now, will not entitle to any sort of DSCI Privacy Certification. ### Privacy Principles based Assessment: (DAF-P) ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp)**Assessment Objectives:** DSCI pioneered the DSCI Privacy Framework (DPF©) which promotes best privacy practices in nine areas. DSCI has been encouraging its adoption by the Indian industry since the publication of DPF© in 2010. The framework has received good response from the industry and it has been adopted by some large enterprises to establish their privacy programs. As part of DPF©, DSCI has also developed DSCI Privacy Principles which are based on the study and analysis of global privacy principles including those of FIPPs, OECD, EU, APEC, etc. DSCI Assessment Framework for Privacy (DAF-P)© is the logical progression of DPF© and can be used as the much required instrument to provide privacy assurance to external and internal stakeholders. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp)**Assessment Areas:** The privacy principles represent the core of privacy protection, and privacy concerns, till date, have more or less been addressed through use of privacy principles. There exist a lot of commonalities in existing data protection regimes, in how they use privacy principles as a tool to address privacy concerns. DSCI has identified nine fundamental Privacy Principles which are derived from globally accepted principles of privacy. These nine principles form a superset of privacy principles. Concepts such as data minimization, privacy by design, privacy enhancing technologies, individual control etc. can be subsumed under these privacy principles. These principles are intended to provide the baseline level of privacy protection to all individual data subjects and end users.

These principles reflect the need for an assurance level that an organization should create in its transactions with the consumers and in its practices to keep intact privacy requirements. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp)**Assessment Questionnaire:** The questionnaire has been divided into ten areas, corresponding to nine principles, with consent & choice having separate set of questions. Questions in each of these areas have been designed in a manner that ensures that the objective of each principle is met in implementation. In designing the questions, lot of emphasis was put on identifying all the possible perspectives / aspects related to the implementation of each privacy principle. These principles were mapped to different scenarios and the different levels (process or organizational) at which they can be implemented, in order to give more meaning and practicality to the assessment questions. To keep the assessment questionnaire contemporary, evolving issues, trends, approaches and practices were also taken into consideration by referring to latest discussions, new privacy approaches and principles, proposed revisions of privacy regulations and issues in the implementation of privacy principles. This approach, based on global privacy principles, is relevant for organizations having global operations. The assessment questionnaire is primarily intended to be used as a self-assessment tool. We have also designed an assessment questionnaire for helping organizations assess compliance against the privacy principles prescribed under section 43A of the IT (Amendment) Act, 2008 that can be used by the companies having operations in India. # DSCI Security Framework (DSF©) ###### Overview DSCI Security Framework (DSF©) is comprised of 16 disciplines that are organized in four layers. This section compiles practices under each discipline. DSCI Security Framework brings a fresh outlook to the security initiatives of an organization by focusing on each individual discipline of security. Each security discipline, as depicted in DSF©, has evolved with very specific approaches to address the specific challenges faced by it. Specific trends and practices have been emerging to address the specific requirements of an individual discipline. The security market, both technology products and services, has solution offerings specific to an individual discipline. Security profession is charting a path of specialization in these individual security disciplines. DSCI believes that the time has come for an organization to focus on individual disciplines and strive to achieve excellence in it. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/DSCISecurityFramework.webp) ### Key features ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/approach-1.webp) Approach to the Security Discipline DSCI believes that there is a significant requirement of discussing the approaches, trends and practices that are driving an individual discipline. This section of each discipline articulates DSCI approach towards the discipline under discussion. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/maturity-1.webp) Strategy for the Security Discipline DSCI also believes that each security discipline deserves a strategic treatment that will not only mature its endeavour but also optimize the resources and efforts deployed. For each discipline, DSCI recommend approaches and processes that help take a strategic review of an organization’s initiative. This section will help managers to provide a strategic direction to the organization’s initiatives in each discipline. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/practices-1.webp) Best Practices for the Security Discipline DSCI recognizes a need for providing a detailed guidance for systematically planning and implementing security in the organisation. Under each discipline this section, throughout the DSF©, compiles the best practices for the security implementer. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/strategy-1.webp) Maturity of the Security Discipline DSCI believes in assessment of the outcomes and for fair assessment comprehension of appropriate parameters is an obligation. The DSF© has defined the maturity criteria for each of the discipline under this section. ### The best practices as per DSF© include ##### ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp) Security Strategy and Policy (SSP) ##### ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp) Security (SCM) ##### ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp) Threat and Vulnerability Management (TVM) ##### ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp) User Access and Privilege Management (UAP) ##### ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/check-1.webp) Business Continuity & Disaster Recovery Management (BDM) ##### This section compiles practices under each discipline. DSCI Security Framework brings a fresh outlook to the security initiatives of an organization by focusing on each individual discipline of security. Each security discipline, as depicted in DSF©, has evolved with very specific approaches to address the specific challenges faced by it. Specific trends and practices have been emerging to address the specific requirements of an individual discipline. The security market, both technology products and services, has solution offerings specific to an individual discipline. Security profession is charting a path of specialization in these individual security disciplines. DSCI believes that the time has come for an organization to focus on individual disciplines and strive to achieve excellence in it. ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/DSCISecurityFramework.webp) ### Key features ![](https://www.dsci.in/files/content/media/images/2023/approach-1.webp) Approach to the Security Discipline DSCI believes that there is a significant requirement of discussing the approaches, trends and practices that are driving an individual discipline.
